# DDD Domain-Driven Design Standards

## Rich Domain Model Principles

> **Business logic must be inside domain objects, not in the Service layer.**

The Service layer only orchestrates (coordinates use cases) and does not contain business rules.

## Entity Standards

### Must Have

- Unique identifier (Id)
- Contains business behavior methods
- Self-validating (at construction/change time)
- State changes exposed through methods

### Must NOT Have

- Public setters
- Direct field modification (use business methods)
- Anemic Domain Model (only getter/setter)

```java
// ✅ Rich Domain Model
public class Order extends AggregateRoot {
    private OrderId id;
    private OrderStatus status;

    public void place() {
        if (this.status != OrderStatus.DRAFT) {
            throw new OrderInvalidStateException("Only draft orders can be placed");
        }
        this.status = OrderStatus.PLACED;
        addDomainEvent(new OrderPlacedEvent(this.id));
    }

    // State can only be changed through business methods
    // No public setter
}

// ❌ Anemic Domain Model
public class Order {
    private OrderId id;
    private OrderStatus status;

    // Only getter/setter, no business logic
    public OrderStatus getStatus() { return status; }
    public void setStatus(OrderStatus status) { this.status = status; }
}
```

## Value Object Standards

### Must Have

- Immutable (no setters, all fields final)
- No unique identifier
- Equality based on attribute values
- Self-validating

### Implementation

```java
// ✅ Java Record (Recommended)
public record Money {
    private final BigDecimal amount;
    private final Currency currency;

    public Money {
        if (amount == null || amount.compareTo(BigDecimal.ZERO) < 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Amount must be non-negative");
        }
        Objects.requireNonNull(currency);
    }

    public Money add(Money other) {
        if (!this.currency.equals(other.currency)) {
            throw new CurrencyMismatchException();
        }
        return new Money(this.amount.add(other.amount), this.currency);
    }
}

// Usage
Money price = new Money(BigDecimal.valueOf(100), Currency.USD);
// price.add() returns new instance, original unchanged
Money total = price.add(Money.of(50, Currency.USD));
```

## Aggregate Standards

### Design Principles

- Aggregates are **consistency boundaries**
- Access externally through the **Aggregate Root**
- Strong consistency within aggregate, eventual consistency between aggregates
- Aggregates should be small (one aggregate = one transaction)

### Standards

```java
// ✅ Aggregate Root
public class Order extends AggregateRoot {
    private List<OrderLine> lines;

    // External access only through aggregate root
    public void addLine(Product product, int quantity) {
        validateQuantity(quantity);
        lines.add(new OrderLine(product.getId(), quantity));
    }

    // Return immutable view
    public List<OrderLine> getLines() {
        return Collections.unmodifiableList(lines);
    }

    // No public setter
}

// ❌ Incorrect: Exposing internal entities
public class BadOrder {
    public List<OrderLine> lines;  // Directly exposed
}
```

## Repository Standards

### Interface Location

- Interfaces defined in **Domain layer**
- Implementations in **Infrastructure layer**

### Design Principles

- Operate only on aggregate roots
- Return aggregate roots or value objects
- Do not return JPA Entities

```java
// ✅ Domain layer: Interface definition
package com.ai.domain.repository;

public interface OrderRepository {
    Optional<Order> findById(OrderId id);
    void save(Order order);
    void delete(OrderId id);
}

// ✅ Infrastructure layer: Implementation
package com.ai.infrastructure.persistence;

@Repository
public class JpaOrderRepository implements OrderRepository {
    @Override
    public Optional<Order> findById(OrderId id) {
        return repository.findById(id.value())
            .map(entityMapper::toDomain);
    }
}
```

## Domain Service Standards

### Use Cases

- Business logic spanning multiple entities
- Operations not belonging to any single entity

### Design Principles

- Stateless
- Accept domain objects as parameters
- Do not hold references to domain objects

```java
// ✅ Domain Service
public class PricingService {
    
    public Money calculatePrice(List<CartItem> items, Customer customer) {
        Money subtotal = items.stream()
            .map(item -> item.getProduct().getPrice().multiply(item.getQuantity()))
            .reduce(Money.ZERO, Money::add);

        if (customer.isVip()) {
            return subtotal.multiply(0.9); // VIP 10% discount
        }
        return subtotal;
    }
}

// ❌ Incorrect: Service takes all business logic
public class BadOrderService {
    public void placeOrder(Order order) {
        // Too much business logic in Service
        if (order.getLines().isEmpty()) throw new EmptyOrderException();
        if (order.getTotal().isNegative()) throw new InvalidAmountException();
        // ...
    }
}
```

## Domain Event Standards

### Definition

```java
// ✅ Immutable event
public record OrderPlacedEvent(
    OrderId orderId,
    CustomerId customerId,
    Money totalAmount,
    Instant occurredAt
) {}

// ✅ Aggregate root publishes events
public class Order extends AggregateRoot {
    private List<DomainEvent> events = new ArrayList<>();

    public void place() {
        // Business logic
        this.status = OrderStatus.PLACED;
        // Publish event
        events.add(new OrderPlacedEvent(id, customerId, totalAmount, Instant.now()));
    }

    @Override
    public List<DomainEvent> pullDomainEvents() {
        List<DomainEvent> pulled = new ArrayList<>(events);
        events.clear();
        return pulled;
    }
}
```

## Common Anti-Patterns

| Anti-Pattern | Symptoms | Correction |
|-------------|----------|------------|
| Anemic Domain Model | Entity only has getter/setter | Move business logic into Entity |
| Too Rich | All logic in Entity | Use Domain Service appropriately |
| Large Aggregate | One aggregate contains entire system | Split aggregates |
| Direct reference between aggregates | `order.getCustomer()` crosses boundary | Use CustomerId |
| Repository operates on non-aggregate-root | `save(OrderLine line)` | Operate only on aggregate roots |
